<div id="review_2510303512" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2510303512" />
    <a title="Ann-Marie &quot;Cookie M.&quot;" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/58567012-ann-marie-cookie-m"><img alt="Ann-Marie &quot;Cookie M.&quot;" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1607273374p2/58567012.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2510303512?book_show_action=true">Jan 10, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Ann-Marie &quot;Cookie M.&quot;" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Ann-Marie &quot;Cookie M.&quot;" href="/user/show/58567012-ann-marie-cookie-m">Ann-Marie &quot;Cookie M.&quot;</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Kindle Edition " href="/book/show/40785049-lights-on-the-sea">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2510303512" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer2753933192737481328"><strong>A nice story</strong><br/><br/> Harold and Mary Rose Grapes are only partly alive since their son died 35 years ago, full of guilt, blame, unshed tears, isolation. They live in a house on a cliff overlooking the sea. But the cliff is eroding, and their house is no longer safe for them to stay in.<br/> That is the situation at the start of &quot;Lights on the Sea,&quot; a tale that I am sure was an allegory for something that I was just too thickheaded to figure out.<br/> The story unfolded beautifully, the adventures of the couple, t</span>
  <span id="freeText2753933192737481328" style="display:none"><strong>A nice story</strong><br /><br /> Harold and Mary Rose Grapes are only partly alive since their son died 35 years ago, full of guilt, blame, unshed tears, isolation. They live in a house on a cliff overlooking the sea. But the cliff is eroding, and their house is no longer safe for them to stay in.<br /> That is the situation at the start of "Lights on the Sea," a tale that I am sure was an allegory for something that I was just too thickheaded to figure out.<br /> The story unfolded beautifully, the adventures of the couple, their strange journey, the way they cared for each other were all told in rhythmic flow.<br /> I was bothered by the feeling that I was missing something, that this was intended to be more than a story of a couple at the end of their lives breaking free from regret and learning to live the life they have. <br /> Or maybe that's all this was, a nice story. It could have been more.</span>
  <a data-text-id="2753933192737481328" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


